Subject: [PATCH 10/11] =?UTF-8?q?T14:=20automatic=20connect=20=E2=80=94=20?=
 =?UTF-8?q?broker=20URL,=20headless=20pairing,=20auto-stream?=
MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=UTF-8
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 8bit

SmartClassroom T14 — completes the "zero user input" KPI. A moonlight://
connect URL now drives pairing and streaming with no dialogs or clicks: the
user clicks the portal connect button and lands in the stream.

  * URL gains a `broker` parameter (moonlight://connect?...&broker=<url>) so
    Moonlight knows which Broker to POST the PIN to. Threaded through the
    `connect` CLI parser (--broker), main.cpp URL expansion/dispatch,
    NvComputer::pendingBrokerUrl (ephemeral, like the T13 token fields), and
    ComputerManager::requestConnect / stashPendingConnect.

  * Headless pairing — ComputerManager::beginHeadlessPairing generates a PIN,
    starts the local pairing handshake and concurrently asks the Broker to
    relay that PIN (ScBrokerClient). NvPairingManager::pair gains a bounded
    phase-1 ("getservercert") timeout for the headless path so a never-
    arriving PIN (Broker down) fails instead of hanging forever; interactive
    pairing keeps the infinite wait. PendingPairingTask carries a `headless`
    flag so headless completions report through a private slot, keeping the
    public pairingCompleted signal exclusively interactive (the GUI / CLI
    pair listeners would otherwise raise a duplicate error dialog).

  * Auto-connect orchestration — a ComputerManager state machine
    (ScAcIdle/ScAcPairing/ScAcWaitingForApps), driven idempotently by host
    state changes, pairs the host headlessly if needed, finds the "Desktop"
    app and creates a Session, then emits autoStreamSessionReady. A 90s
    overall timeout guards the flow.

  * main.qml shows a modal progress popup while the flow runs and pushes
    StreamSegue with the ready Session (the CliStartStreamSegue hand-off
    pattern). On failure/timeout the popup closes, an error dialog shows and
    the user is left on the standard PcView UI — the manual fallback.
